Step 0: Pull Node.js Docker image
docker pull node:20

What happens:

Downloads the Node.js 20 image from Docker Hub.
Contains:
Node runtime (node)
npm (package manager)
Linux filesystem to run Node apps
✅ This does not create your React project; it only gives you an environment to run Node/React commands.
Step 1: Run a container for Node + React dev
docker run -it -p 3000:3000 --name react-dev -v C:/Users/ronak/react-project:/app -w /app node:20 bash

Explanation of flags:

Flag	Meaning
-it	Run in interactive mode and attach a terminal (you can type commands).
-p 3000:3000	Map container port 3000 → host port 3000, so you can access React in your browser.
--name react-dev	Give the container a name so you can easily restart or remove it later.
-v C:/Users/ronak/react-project:/app	Mount your host folder to container’s /app folder. Changes in container or host are reflected both ways.
-w /app	Set working directory inside container to /app.
node:20	Use Node 20 image.
bash	Start a shell inside the container.

What happens:

Container is created and started.
You are inside /app folder in container.
Node.js and npm are ready to use.
Step 2: Check folder inside container
ls
You should see your host folder contents (if already existing).
This is because of the -v mount.
Step 3: Create React app (if not already created)
npx create-react-app login-app

What happens:

npx runs create-react-app without installing globally.
Generates folder structure:
login-app/
├─ src/
│  ├─ App.js
│  ├─ App.css
│  ├─ index.js
│  └─ Login.js (you can create)
├─ public/
├─ package.json
├─ node_modules/
└─ ...
Everything appears both inside container and on your host folder (C:/Users/ronak/react-project/login-app) because of the volume mount.

Important: ✅ Node container provides the environment; React app structure is created by create-react-app.

Step 4: Enter React project folder
cd login-app
Moves into your React app folder.
Step 5: Install dependencies
npm install

What happens:

Installs all dependencies listed in package.json into node_modules.
Output may include:
up to date, audited 1313 packages
268 packages looking for funding
26 vulnerabilities (9 low, 3 moderate, 14 high)
⚠️ Warnings about vulnerabilities or npm updates are normal — they do not prevent your app from running.
Step 6: Start React dev server
npm start -- --host 0.0.0.0

Explanation:

npm start → runs react-scripts start.
--host 0.0.0.0 → makes the server accessible from host machine, not just inside container.
Output looks like:
Compiled successfully!
Local:            http://localhost:3000
On Your Network:  http://172.17.0.2:3000
Open host browser → http://localhost:3000.
Step 7: Edit React code
Edit on host (not inside container) for hot reload:
C:/Users/ronak/react-project/login-app/src/App.js
C:/Users/ronak/react-project/login-app/src/Login.js
Any changes you save are immediately reflected in browser.
Step 8: Stop or restart container
Stop container:
docker stop react-dev
Restart container:
docker start -ai react-dev
Removes container (if you want fresh start):
docker rm react-dev
Step 9: Notes about Node + React in Docker
Concept	Explanation
Node container	Just the runtime environment for Node/React apps.
React project (create-react-app)	Creates actual app files and folder structure.
Mounted host folder	Syncs container folder with host → edit on host, run in container.
npm start -- --host 0.0.0.0	Allows browser to access dev server from host.
Hot reload	Works because mounted folder updates container files in real time.

